  "text": "Systems with strong negative correlations may also represent cultivation-depensation processes [CITATION_1] . According to this hypothesis, dominant predator fishes (i.e. cod) prey on forage fish species (i.e. herring), which in turn compete with larval and juvenile age classes of the predator, indirectly increasing recruitment success in subsequent years. If harvest reduces predator biomass below some critical threshold, depensation may occur as forage fish populations are released from predatory control and increasingly prey upon or compete with juvenile predators for mutual resources. We find some evidence of cultivation-depensation in 3 systems in particular (NORT, GoM, and sGoSL) and possibly GB and EBS. In these systems, herring biomass and ASP increased over time, coincident to low cod biomass and ASP that persisted even after harvest pressure on that species was reduced or eliminated. Additional analyses are needed to evaluate mechanisms driving this potentially important relationship.",
